        <h3 data-uuid="8d94c67cf66e47449609d3cf71809f30">Cotton Trade</h3>
        <p data-uuid="e1e9e5e2c881426391761bacee627fe7"> In an 1858 speech before the U.S. Senate, South Carolina politician James Henry Hammond declared, “Cotton is King!” Without cotton, Hammond claimed, the global economy would fail. He believed that southern cotton was one of the most valuable resources in the world. Southern cotton was used to make cloth in England and the North. Many southerners shared Hammond’s viewpoints about cotton. Professor David Christy used colorful language to describe the crop’s importance.</p>
        <section class="pullquote_wrapper" data-uuid="16e0f71ded9c4e2e87aac915195eac5f">
            <p class="pullquote hang" data-uuid="ff6e6af629af44b4b3c1e53aca845695">“King cotton is a&#160;<b><a href="[remark:857fd284eb1841f9b4dd193b52706874]"> profound</a>&#160;</b>statesman, and knows what measures will best&#160;<b><a href="[remark:7fd7d31baf244f2a99eaf8a588918e2f]"> sustain</a></b> his throne.”</p>
            <div class="pullquote_attribution_wrapper" data-uuid="d39ee89667af48e0a4caa0f68398a084">
                <p class="pullquote_address" data-uuid="ee5050a8042b4f02ab40537f635684a5">—David Christy</p>
                <p class="p_source" data-uuid="0eb9083de9cd40d8968a5d210c2cbb4f"> <i>Cotton Is King</i></p>
                
            </div>
        </section>
        <p data-uuid="26a2019b46ee4c9ead2c5f630a6ff9d6">The cotton boom made the South a major player in world trade. Great Britain became the South’s most valued foreign trading partner. Southerners also sold tons of cotton to the growing textile industry in the northeastern United States. This increased trade led to the growth of major port cities in the South, including Charleston, South Carolina; Savannah, Georgia; and New Orleans, Louisiana.</p>
        <p data-uuid="f5a0a2b76bef4a6a86c1843db3229873">In these cities, crop brokers called <b><dfn title="factor">factors</dfn></b> managed the cotton trade. Farmers sold their cotton to merchants, who then made deals with the factors. Merchants and factors also arranged loans for farmers who needed to buy supplies. They often advised farmers on how to invest profits. Once farmers got their cotton to the port cities, factors arranged for transportation aboard trading ships.</p>
